text: It is challenges in terms of doing the work, but it's opportunities because not everyone will be in a position to tackle those challenges. I think on the big data part, it's absolutely right. There are lots and lots of bonds out there with their finite life that I was talking about before and their characteristic details. And we spend, and we spent at the start of the firm, a lot of time on getting the details and the mapping right. So looking across the universe of corporate bonds, you've got to make sure that they're mapped to the right issuer. That's the issuer who's going to provide the economic support, not just the subsidiary. So there's some degree of complexity in that. You've got to think about getting the characteristics right, like the domicile, the callability, anything else that's unusual about the bond, green bonds these days, et cetera. Having got all of those characteristics correct, we also got to map to the equity because there's information from the equity market that can be very useful. And clearly, with the presence of corporate actions, et cetera, that process isn't always simple. So once you've done that work, you can kind of solve the big data challenge. And then probably the next area in which the big data challenge kind of appears is in terms of optimization. So some folks take simple ways around this. A lot of the academic papers pick a representative bond for each issuer that might vary through time, but they always have a one-to-one mapping between issuer and bond. We chose not to do that because we wanted to model the whole spectrum. Going back to your point about Coca-Cola stock before and whether there might be liquidity in one bond or the other, if you only model one bond, then you can't really say, what happens when liquidity dries up in that. So we decided to model all bonds in the universe. But the consequence of that is you have to decide whether your model is going to take a cross-issuer exposure, so exposure between issuers, or whether it's going to trade bonds within the issuers, going long one bond and short another one for the same issuer. Getting that balance right is another sort of big data complexity. And then on the new issues point you raised, kind of like the small data. Yes, we have that issue. When a new issue comes along that it's going to be released tomorrow, we need to know whether we're going to buy it, whether we're going to go short it. And you have to make that decision without any data. We have to decide whether it's decent value, whether it's going to be print expensive when it's issued. And maybe more importantly, we have to be able to model the risk of that bond. And I guess that's actually what makes the factor risk approach that I was talking about key. Because with factor risk models, as you know, as opposed to statistical risk models, you don't actually have to have a price history. All you need is the bond's characteristics in order to model its factor risk, at least. So that's the way that we solve that challenge, this term.
